<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910131-0016</DOCNO><DOCID>910131-0016.</DOCID><HL>   California Institutions Mull   Tobacco-Stock Divestitures</HL><DATE>01/31/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   MO LABOR</CO><IN>TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)</IN><LP>   Several public and private institutions in California saidthey plan to review a request from state health officials todivest themselves of tobacco-company investments &quot;in theinterest of promoting health.&quot;   &quot;The request will be reviewed, I'm sure, by the board ofregents,&quot; said a University of California spokesman. Thenine-campus university has a $50 million investment in PhilipMorris Cos. bonds but doesn't own any tobacco-company stocks,the spokesman said.</LP><TEXT>   Jim Mosman, chief executive officer of the CaliforniaState Teachers' Retirement System, said the request probablywould be discussed at a board meeting next week. The fund hasabout $325 million in tobacco-related investments.   A Stanford University spokeswoman said thetobacco-investment issue has been under discussion since lastfall by two university committees, one representing the boardof trustees and another representing students, faculty, staffand alumni. Stanford's tobacco investments currently have amarket value of &quot;less than $18 million,&quot; she said.   University of Southern California treasurer WilliamHromadka has said that the university's committee oninvestments and social responsibility would consider thetobacco issue this spring.   Officials at the Public Employees' Retirement Systemcouldn't be reached. State health officials have said theretirement fund has about $300 million in tobacco-relatedinvestments.</TEXT></DOC>